These marks and these parallels are, as I take it, of sufficient authority in themselves to estab- lish a common authorship for Selimus and the work that goes under Marlowe's name. Fortunately, how- ever, we have very strong corroborative testimony in favour of Marlowe’s claim, as 1 shall show further on.

Note how Faustus and Selimus borrow kindred material from the same canto of Spenser’s poem, and how this material helps to give expression to the atheism that is rampant in both plays.

The following partly describes the appearance of Sir Trevisan after his escape from the Misereaunt :—

In fowle reproch of knighthoodes fair degree, About his neck an hempen rope he weares, That with his glistring armes does ill agree. Book 1. canto ix. stanza xxii.

Compare :—

Methought, Muscam, 1 beheld thy neck So often folded in my loving arms, In foul disgrace of Bashaw's fair degree With a vile halter basely compassed. “ selimus,'’ 11. 2227-30.
